	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_356081">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_356081">Mages of Norath: Information Guide<br />
<br />
Some say the world will end in fire,<br />
Some say in ice.<br />
From what I've tasted of desire<br />
I hold with those who favor fire.<br />
But if it had to perish twice,<br />
I think I know enough of hate<br />
To know that for destruction ice<br />
Is also great<br />
And would suffice. <br />
-Robert Frost<br />
<br />
Mission Statement: This post is meant to be a complete description for anyone interesting in the mage class and wants to know what they are all about in EQII. This will be helpful <br />
<br />
I. Class Tree<br />
II. Races<br />
III. Magic System in EQII<br />
IV. Screenshots<br />
V. City Guilds/ Trainers<br />
VI. Moorguard’s Madness<br />
VII. Links<br />
VIII. In-Game Support for helping newcomers<br />
<br />
I. <br />
<br />
A) ADVENTURING CLASSES<br />
<br />
The class tree is divided into branches, upon reaching level six the player can choose if he wants to become a fighter, scout, priest, or mage. We’ll assume safely that you are interested in selecting the mage archetype. From here you will have 9 more levels to decide upon your class, getting a feel for the characters that suit you best. Let us take a look of your choices:<br />
<br />
Sorcerer - Sorcerers are experts of all forms of mystical attacks and spells that weaken the mystical abilities of their opponents. Fearsome in battle, sorcerers wield powerful arcane forces. <br />
<br />
Translation: This will be the direct damage wizards, if you desire pets this is not your choice.<br />
<br />
Enchanter - Enchanters use mystical forces to beguile and control their enemies. By instilling confusion and misdirection in the minds of their adversaries, enchanters give their comrades the advantage in battle. <br />
<br />
Translation: Charming-Mezzing-Hasting is the name of the game, great for groups but intensive concentration required on timing.<br />
<br />
Summoner - Summoners can call forth powerful creatures of Norath and bend them to their will. Though the command a variety of mystical forces, the summoners foremost weapons are the monsters they control. <br />
<br />
Translation: This will be the class that fans of necromancers in Diablo II want to play. <br />
<br />
Overall all these classes will have some overlap to ensure they are useful in group spots, but this is what they bring to the table. Furthermore, in 15 more levels they begin to specialize, while primarily being the same they will use different methods (often foils of each other: good versus evil).<br />
<br />
For the Sorcerer:<br />
<br />
Wizard - Wizards are masters of the arcane arts who tap into the elemental powers of fire and ice. Wielding these powerful forces, wizards can inflict startling devastation upon their enemies.<br />
<br />
*This is primarily where the Robert Frost Epigraph applies to*<br />
<br />
Warlock - Warlocks manipulate the destructive forces of poison and disease to obliterate their foes. They are masters of death and decay who deal devastating damage and pain to their opponents.<br />
<br />
For the Enchanter:<br />
<br />
Illusionist - Illusionists use arcane power to confound and befuddle their enemies. They also are able to boost the offensive and defensive capabilities of their allies.<br />
<br />
Coercer - Coercers dominate the minds of the weak and hurl their foes into paralyzing states of confusion and catatonia. They can also enhance the mental abilities and combat prowess of their allies. <br />
<br />
For the Summoner:<br />
<br />
Conjuror - Conjurors summon forth powerful elemental beings that obey their master's every command. Ripped from domains of the fire, air, soil, and water, these enslaved minions make very powerful servants and bodyguards.<br />
<br />
Necromancer - Necromancers summon the dead and imbue them with unnatural life. These pitiful but powerful creatures are slaves to their masters until the grave claims them once more. Lords of death and decay, these powerful mages strike fear into the hearts of their enemies. <br />
<br />
The differences in the classes might seem trivial, but as you specialize your role becomes more and more unique, thus making you more desirable in groups or soloing. Seemingly trivial, these subclasses will define your role in the high end game experience, and since the game is targeted for 24 people max on a raid, these choices are quite important.<br />
<br />
B) TRADE SKILLS<br />
<br />
The last set of classes are not really classes per say, but artisan roles. With a separate experience pool set aside for trade skills, all classes can be 1 adventuring class and 1 trade skill class simultaneously. While some might seem more apt to mages, these are for profit and stimulation of the player-driven economy. Thus you may choose to be a wizard smith, although that would require you to trade for your Scholarly goods. Without further ado, the classes are:<br />
<br />
Builder - Builders are skilled crafters who specialize in the creation of material goods. From well-made weapons to furniture and clothing, builders make a variety of valuable commodities.<br />
	Crafter - Crafters are specialists in the creation of leather, cloth, and wooden 	products. They build furnishings for the home, including items of prestige and 	distinctions.<br />
<br />
	Smith - Smiths are experts in making the finest weapons and armor available. 	Their skill in forging the raw metals of the earth into sharp swords and sturdy plate 	is second to none. <br />
<br />
<br />
Scholar - Scholars focus on the study of mystical artifacts and relics. They specialize in deciphering mysterious objects and enchanting mundane items with mystical power.<br />
<br />
	Alchemist - Alchemists are scholars who specialize in brewing magical elixirs. 	These potions imbue the drinker with temporary mystical power and augment their 	abilities.<br />
<br />
	Sage - Sages interpret mystical artifacts and decipher long-lost languages as they 	are uncovered. These learned scholars scribe spells and scrolls, imbuing mere 	parchments with mystical might.<br />
<br />
In summation, trade skills were important in Everquest because they sometimes were intricate parts to elaborate quests. So if you are having difficult finding a group I recommend spending some time trying this out.<br />
<br />
<br />
II. Races- Divided by good mage choices, and poor mage choices. The difference being starting statistics. [These are all my opinions as no final word has been released on stats]. This upcoming list is meant to be helpful to anyone thinks that an ogre mage would be good because they are in Dungeons and Dragons.<br />
<br />
